            <h1 style="font-family: 'Calistoga', cursive;">Java</h1>
            <h3>Classes</h3>
            <p>A class in Java serves as a blueprint or template for creating objects. It defines the structure and
                behavior of objects belonging to that class. Classes can have attributes, also known as fields or
                instance variables, which represent the data or state of the objects. These fields can have various data
                types, including primitive types like integers and doubles, or reference types such as other classes.</p>
            <p>Classes also contain methods, which are functions associated with objects of the class, defining the
                behavior or actions that these objects can perform. Methods can take parameters and return values,
                making them essential for the functionality of the class</p>
            <p>Java offers access modifiers like <b>public</b>,<b> private</b>,<b> protected</b> and package-private
                (default) to control the visibility and accessibility of class members.</p>
            <hr>
            <h3>Objects</h3>
            <p>Objects are instances of classes, created using the <b>new</b> keyword followed by the class constructor. Each object represents a unique entity with its own set of attributes and state. Objects encapsulate data and methods, allowing you to interact with and manipulate the class's behavior.</p>
            <p> Instantiating an object allocates memory for it and invokes the constructor to set its initial values. Objects are the building blocks of object-oriented programming in Java, enabling organized code development. By creating multiple objects from the same class, you can manage complex systems with ease, as each object operates independently while adhering to the class's blueprint</p>
            <hr>
            <h3>Example</h3>
            <div class="code_container">
                <div class="code_wrapper">
                    <pre>
                        <code id="code" class="language-Java">
                            // Define a class called 'Person'
                            class Person {
                                // Declare an instance variable
                                String name;
                            
                                // Define a constructor to initialize the 'name' attribute
                                public Person(String name) {
                                    this.name = name;
                                }
                            
                                // Define a method to display the person's name
                                public void display() {
                                    System.out.println("I am " + name);
                                }
                            }
                            public class MyClass {
                            
                                public static void main(String[] args) {
                                    // Create an object of the 'Person' class
                                    Person person1 = new Person("Chandler Bing");
                            
                                    // Call the 'display' method to show the person's name
                                    person1.display();
                                }
                            }
                        </code>
